2025-01-26

Prepared by: Roy Mwavita

Introduction

In the realm of data analysis, real-world data sets are rarely clean or perfect. They often contain missing values, inconsistencies, and errors, presenting a unique challenge for analysts and data scientists.

This document showcases a hands-on approach to cleaning and exploring the Dirty Cafe Sales data set, a synthetic data set containing 10,000 rows of sales dataset intentionally designed to mimic real-world imperfections.

Objective

The objective of this exploratory data analysis (EDA) is twofold:

  1. Data Cleaning: Addressing missing values, correcting inconsistencies, and handling errors to ensure the data set is ready for analysis.

  2. Exploratory Data Analysis: Uncovering patterns, trends, and insights hidden within the data to provide actionable recommendations.

By working through this data set, we demonstrate essential data wrangling and EDA techniques that can be applied.

This exercise emphasizes the importance of transforming raw, messy data into clean, meaningful information that drives decision-making using R programming.

To clean this data set using Tidymodels principles in R, we’ll follow a structured approach.

Here’s the step-by-step process:

1. Import Data

Using pacman::p_load to load libraries in R is a convenient way to manage packages efficiently.

Unlike library(), it first checks if a package is installed and installs it automatically if missing, then loads it. This ensures all required libraries are available without interruptions or errors during runtime.

rm(list = ls()) #Clear the environment if you have active objects

# Load necessary libraries
pacman::p_load(
  tidyverse,  
  janitor,    
  here,       
  magrittr,
  skimr
)


Here’s a breakdown of why and how we use each package in the example:

tidyverse:

  • A suite of packages like dplyr, ggplot2, and readr for data manipulation, analysis, and visualization.

  • Example: Use dplyr to filter, summarize, and transform data, and ggplot2 for high-quality data visualizations.

janitor:

  • Simplifies data cleaning tasks, such as standardizing column names (clean_names()) and identifying missing data.

  • Example: Quickly clean messy column names for consistency in large datasets.

here:

  • Handles file paths relative to the project’s root directory, avoiding hardcoding paths.

  • Example: Use here("filename.csv/xlsx") to load or save data files in a project folder without worrying about the working directory.

magrittr:

  • Provides intuitive piping (%>%) and assignment operators (%<>%) to write cleaner, more readable code.

  • Example: The %<>% operator modifies and assigns data transformations directly to the object.

skimr:

  • Provides summary statistics about variables in data frames, tibbles, data tables and vectors.

  • Example: skim() presents results for every column; the statistics it provides depend on the class of the variable.

Upon examining the 10 rows, you can deduce the following:

  • Transaction.ID: This column lists all unique IDs for transactions related to purchases.

  • Item: The second column specifies the items purchased, such as Coffee, Cake, Cookie, etc.

  • Quantity: The third column indicates the number of items bought.

  • Price.Per.Unit: The fourth column shows the price per item. When multiplied by the quantity, it results in the Total.Spent amount in the fifth column, although we may need to recalculate to verify accuracy

  • Payment.Method: The sixth column details the payment method used (e.g., Credit Card, Cash, Digital Wallet).

  • Location: This column specifies where the purchase was made (e.g., In store, Takeaway).

  • Transaction.Date: The final column records the date of each transaction.

Expectations

From these insights we can expect to uncover the following:

  • What products to stock more based on sales volume.

  • What payment options are most convenient for customers.

  • Seasonal trends or days with higher sales activity.

  • Location preferences for strategic marketing.

b. Fix Column Names.

Referring to columns like Transaction.ID and Price.Per.Unit can be problematic.

To avoid issues, ensure that column names adhere to the snake_case naming convention.

For example, rename them to transaction_id and price_per_unit.

 
#Use the clean_names() function from the janitor library to remove any symbols and convert column names to lowercase.

dataset %<>% 
  clean_names()

#View column names

3. Transform

a. Handle missing or erroneous data.

Replace all occurrences of empty strings (““),”UNKNOWN”, and “Error” throughout the dataset with NA.

Why we use NA instead of empty strings(““)?

  1. NA is the standard placeholder for missing values in R.

  2. This ensures consistent handling of missing data during analysis.

#Replace blanks (""), "UNKNOWN", and "Error" with NA
dataset %<>%
  mutate(across(
    everything(),
    ~ ifelse(. %in% c("UNKNOWN", "ERROR", ""), NA, .) 
  ))

#Filter only one quantity for each item
price_for_item <- dataset %>% 
  filter(!is.na(item))

#Group each item with the value of prices

pivot_wider_item <- price_for_item %>% 
  group_by(item, price_per_unit) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = item,
    values_from = price_per_unit,
    values_fill = list(price_per_unit = 0)
  ) %>% 
  select(-count) %>% 
  filter(if_any(everything(), ~ . != 0)) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ if_else(. == 0, NA, .)))

fill_price_per_unit <- na_item %>%

iii. Fill NA in quantity with the result of total_spent divided by price_per_unit.

na_quantity <- fill_price_per_unit %>% 
  mutate(
    quantity = case_when(
      is.na(quantity) & !is.na(price_per_unit) & !is.na(total_spent) ~ total_spent / price_per_unit, 
      TRUE ~ quantity  
    )
  )


#Count NA in quantity

na_count <- sum(is.na(na_quantity$quantity)) 

print(na_count)
## [1] 23

iv. Fill NA in price_per_unit with the result of total_spent divided by quantity.

na_price_per_unit <- na_quantity %>% 
  mutate(
    price_per_unit = case_when(
      is.na(price_per_unit) & !is.na(quantity) & !is.na(total_spent) ~ total_spent / quantity, 
      TRUE ~ price_per_unit 
    )
  )


#Count NA in price per unit

na_total_spent <- na_price_per_unit %>% 
  mutate(
    total_spent = case_when(
      is.na(total_spent) & !is.na(quantity) & !is.na(price_per_unit) ~ quantity * price_per_unit,
      TRUE ~ total_spent 
    )
  )

Food for thought: When is it appropriate to drop rows with missing values in some columns?

When It’s Appropriate When It’s Not Appropriate
The Missing Data is Not Critical: Missing values occur in non-essential columns. Example: Irrelevant comments column. The Missing Data is Systematic or Significant: Missing values follow a pattern, potentially introducing bias.
The Proportion of Missing Values is Small: A small percentage of rows have missing values, ensuring the dataset remains representative. The Dataset is Already Small: Dropping rows may reduce representativeness and statistical power.
Missing Data is Random (MCAR): No relationship exists between missingness and other variables. Example: Random survey non-responses. The Missing Data is in Critical Columns: Excludes essential insights. Example: Missing key variables like income.
Alternative Solutions are Not Feasible: Imputation is impractical or unreliable. Example: No clear way to estimate critical missing values. You Plan to Use Imputation or Modeling Techniques: Advanced methods might handle missingness more effectively.
You Need a Clean Dataset: Essential for certain models or visualizations. Example: Machine learning models requiring complete data. The Missing Data Provides Insights: Missingness may indicate trends. Example: Lack of feedback suggesting dissatisfaction.

So should we:

a) Drop rows with missing values

or

b) Impute missing values


We can choose to impute the missing values in item with most frequent value.

#Find most frequent

 most_frequent_item <- dataset_2 %>%
  filter(item != "") %>%          
  count(item, sort = TRUE) %>%   
  slice(1) %>%                    
  pull(item) 
 
 print(most_frequent_item)
## [1] "Cake"
# Replace NA values in the 'item' column with the most frequent value

dataset_impute <- dataset_2 %>%
  mutate(item = ifelse(is.na(item), "Cake", item
))

#Fill NA in total_spent with the result of quantity * price_per_unit

dataset_impute %<>%   
  mutate(
    total_spent = if_else(
      !is.na(quantity) & !is.na(price_per_unit), 
      quantity * price_per_unit, total_spent
    )
  )

#Fill NA in quantity with the result of total_spent / price_per_unit
dataset_impute %<>%
  mutate(
    quantity = if_else(
      !is.na(total_spent) & !is.na(price_per_unit), total_spent/price_per_unit, quantity
    )
  )

Boxplot for Purchase Frequency by Price Category: 

# Create price categories
item_data <- imputed_dataset %>% 
 mutate(price_category = case_when(
    price_per_unit <= 2 ~ "Low",
    price_per_unit <= 4 ~ "Medium",
    TRUE ~ "High"
  ))

#Plot
ggplot(item_data, aes(x = price_category, y = quantity)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = price_category)) +
  labs(title = "Quantity Purchased by Price Category",
       x = "Price Category", y = "Quantity Purchased") +
  theme_minimal()

ANOVA Test 

anova_model <- aov(quantity ~ price_category, data = item_data)
summary(anova_model)
##                  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## price_category    2      2   1.184   0.586  0.557
## Residuals      9977  20166   2.021

Since the Pr(>F) (p-value) is much greater than the threshold of 0.05, it means there is no significant evidence that price_category affects the quantity purchased.

# Extract date parts
imputed_dataset %<>%

daily_sales <- imputed_dataset %>%
